This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with generating coherent and variable utterances in conversation. It also involves the use of neural encoder-decoder models, which are commonly used in natural language processing. 

It could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it involves the use of a mixture model to inject variability into the neural encoder-decoder. 

Additionally, it could belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as it involves the development of a novel approach to improve the performance of neural encoder-decoder models. 

It may also belong to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as it involves the use of neural networks to model sequential data. 

Finally, it could belong to cs.SD (Sound) as it deals with generating coherent and variable utterances in conversation, which is a form of sound-based communication.
